WEBVTT

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:08.240
Hi, my name's Nick Pratap. I'm a pediatric anesthesiologist. This is what I get paid to do,

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:14.400
taking care of kids having procedures done to their hearts. So you might ask, what am I doing

00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:21.600
standing in front of you all here today at PositConf? And it's a good question. So I'd like

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:28.000
to tell you today about my self-guided journey into data science. I'd like to offer some shout

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.919
out to some influences and sources of help that I've had along the way. I'd also like to maybe

00:00:33.919 --> 00:00:39.599
provide a little bit of encouragement to anybody who's on a similar path to me, or perhaps even

00:00:39.599 --> 00:00:46.400
if you know somebody or come across somebody that's on that kind of a path. So the backstory

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:53.919
is that in 2011, I came from London to Cincinnati to learn about quality improvement in healthcare

00:00:53.919 --> 00:00:59.279
at Cincinnati Children's Hospital, which is renowned for that kind of work. And they asked

00:00:59.279 --> 00:01:06.480
me to work on surgery cancellation. Immediately, I could find out that about 5% of procedures were

00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:12.400
cancelled on the day of surgery. And this actually equated to about 5% of operating time as well,

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:18.160
which is important because a lot of the billing is based on time. So through this, we found out

00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:24.639
that the problem of surgery cancellation probably cost about $100,000 a week in terms of potential

00:01:24.639 --> 00:01:31.040
lost revenue, which is a lot of money. But just taking a more human side to it, it was really

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:38.559
difficult and frustrating for families and for staff as well. So I'd just like to take a moment

00:01:38.559 --> 00:01:45.199
to put surgery cancellation in terms of some dimensions of quality, which is what's from the

00:01:45.199 --> 00:01:48.959
Institute of Medicine, which is what people often talk about in healthcare quality.

00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:56.239
Even I didn't know until I came across this paper that about 30% of the global burden of disease

00:01:56.239 --> 00:02:00.720
needs surgery or other procedures under anaesthesia, either for working it up or

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:06.080
for actually treating. So clearly, if surgery is cancelled, the effectiveness of that procedure

00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:13.119
is not going to be realised. I touched already on family-centredness, but I'd like to just mention

00:02:13.119 --> 00:02:17.039
a paper from more than 20 years ago from another major children's hospital.

00:02:17.039 --> 00:02:22.720
They found out that many families drive tens or even hundreds of miles to get to the local

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:29.360
children's hospital. They often have to pay for accommodation. They have to get childcare for

00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:35.360
their other children. Mostly, they're taking time off work and more often than not, that's unpaid.

00:02:35.360 --> 00:02:39.839
So when the surgery is cancelled, it's probably not surprising that they're quite emotional and

00:02:39.839 --> 00:02:47.440
even angry on many occasions. Timeliness, clearly, if the surgery doesn't go ahead and

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:53.119
has to be rescheduled, then it's not being provided in a timely fashion. Efficiency,

00:02:53.119 --> 00:02:57.839
I already touched on that, and the other one that they always talk about is equitability,

00:02:57.839 --> 00:03:02.800
and at the point when we started this, we really didn't know what the impact was.

00:03:03.759 --> 00:03:09.039
So why does children's surgery get cancelled? The number one cause is patient illness.

00:03:09.039 --> 00:03:15.199
So with the kids, it's usually coughs, colds, diarrhoea, vomiting, things that give you a fever,

00:03:15.199 --> 00:03:20.080
which means it's not safe to go ahead with the procedure. The second cause is no-show.

00:03:20.639 --> 00:03:26.960
They don't turn up. The third most frequent we call NPO violation. So in order to have safe

00:03:27.839 --> 00:03:32.960
anaesthesia, you need to have an empty stomach before we begin, and so we give instructions

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:38.320
about when they can safely eat and drink and when they have to stop, and if those are not followed,

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:45.279
then we can't go ahead with the procedure. So we did a few cross-the-board interventions to

00:03:45.279 --> 00:03:50.000
try and reduce our surgery cancellation rate. We came up with some new, more colourful

00:03:51.919 --> 00:03:56.720
instructions for families with some pictures on of when it was okay to eat and what particular

00:03:57.039 --> 00:04:02.479
things were okay at particular times, when to show up. We sent out some text message reminders.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:09.919
And finally, we set up a process that if the pre-op nurses having a phone call a couple of

00:04:09.919 --> 00:04:14.880
days beforehand had any inkling that the kid was sick, then they would have a process to discuss

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:20.640
it with our nurse practitioners and therefore try and avoid cancellation on the day by rescheduling

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:29.200
in advance. So we tested all these interventions, and then we rolled them out across the hospital.

00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:36.640
We were pretty happy that we succeeded in saving about over an hour a day, which was about 17% of

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:43.200
the time, and that was good. But I'm a perfectionist, and so I wanted to work out why

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:48.480
people were still cancelling. And also really being curious about this no-show, the second

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:53.440
most common. So these were people that families didn't arrive, they didn't answer the

00:04:53.440 --> 00:04:57.200
phone when we tried to get hold of them, so we just really didn't know what was going on.

00:04:58.799 --> 00:05:06.320
A lot of my colleagues had opinions. One of the myths that I was told a lot was that dental

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:12.640
patients are the worst for not showing up. So that was kind of interesting, and actually kind of

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:18.079
relevant, because if there was some problem in the dental surgery department that they really weren't

00:05:18.959 --> 00:05:23.119
preparing the families properly, they weren't giving them the right instructions,

00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:28.079
we ought to be able to learn from another department that was informing their families

00:05:28.079 --> 00:05:36.320
better, and therefore be able to help with this situation. I didn't know what to do,

00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:43.440
but I did feel that we needed data. W. Edward Stemming is the guru of quality improvement.

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:49.519
He said, in God we trust, all others must bring data. So he's the first of my influences.

00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:57.519
But what sort of data? So please don't try and read my red slides, they're just to show you

00:05:57.519 --> 00:06:03.200
the morass of overwhelming information that we were trying to deal with. So we did some

00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:07.839
brainstorming, the things that are in the electronic medical record, like what things

00:06:07.839 --> 00:06:13.359
could potentially be associated with cancellation. We came up with a lot, as you can see. We even

00:06:13.519 --> 00:06:19.440
looked outside the medical record, we wondered about the weather, so we got weather data from

00:06:19.440 --> 00:06:24.959
the local airport, which keep good records. I didn't know what to do with this, this was too

00:06:24.959 --> 00:06:31.279
much. You may notice my pictures so far have all been in Excel. Microsoft Excel was not going to

00:06:31.279 --> 00:06:38.079
solve this problem for me. I had a little bit of experience with computers, back from when I was

00:06:38.239 --> 00:06:45.839
nine. My father bought me this computer, and it had one kilobyte of memory, and I learned programming

00:06:45.839 --> 00:06:53.440
basic. From that I have an appreciation of concise and efficient code, but it really was not going to

00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:59.119
help me too much at this point. By the way, Sir Clive Sinclair invented this, also Sir Britt,

00:06:59.119 --> 00:07:06.480
who came up with the electric car before Elon Musk. Who did? Fortunately, I found somebody who

00:07:06.480 --> 00:07:12.720
was able to help me, or at least his writing. The idea of tidy data was really helpful to me,

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:17.440
and I started trying to wrangle some of this data we were getting. This was a long time ago,

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:25.040
so I was using Cliar, and later on the Tidyverse. I didn't use this book because it hadn't been

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:30.320
written then, but I would strongly recommend for anybody at this point now, Alpha Data Science is

00:07:30.320 --> 00:07:37.920
an amazing book. So, I started to do what I now know, but didn't then, would be called exploratory

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:45.760
data analysis. So, this is ggplot. I've graduated a little bit further forward. I wanted to look at

00:07:45.760 --> 00:07:50.480
cancellations over time. Was there any seasonality to the cancellation rate, and it seemed that there

00:07:50.480 --> 00:07:56.079
was, because we've got some variation there. Why could that be? Well, I mentioned patient illness

00:07:56.079 --> 00:08:04.320
as being the most important cause, and I wondered, I got some data from the

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:11.200
hospital's laboratory databases about the tests that were positive for some of the infections that

00:08:11.200 --> 00:08:17.040
we know kids get, you know, viral type stuff, and there was also some variation going on, and it seemed

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:24.399
to my quick look to be kind of similar. So, I started to realize I was going to need to model

00:08:24.399 --> 00:08:31.040
cancellations. Just to go back briefly to quality improvement, we know that when you're able to

00:08:31.040 --> 00:08:36.479
predict something, you might be able to prevent it. So, in this case, we thought we could target support

00:08:36.479 --> 00:08:41.679
to at-risk families if we knew who was at risk. We did a little bit of psychological research

00:08:41.679 --> 00:08:48.400
to try and help, so we knew what sort of interventions we could try. Also, we felt that prediction might

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:55.119
help us with mitigation. So, if we had an idea in advance that particular OR slots might be

00:08:55.919 --> 00:09:01.440
opened up because the families wouldn't show up, then we could slip in some like short notice

00:09:01.440 --> 00:09:08.559
emergency cases. I also had a hope that I might be able to understand cancellation by developing a

00:09:08.559 --> 00:09:18.080
model for it. So, at this point, the most important influence came to me, influencer, I should say.

00:09:18.799 --> 00:09:25.039
It was actually an August, very hot August Sunday. My daughter was just starting at kindergarten,

00:09:25.039 --> 00:09:31.359
and they had an event where the families could get together and meet each other, and I met

00:09:32.239 --> 00:09:39.200
Emily's mum. So, the mother of one of the other kids in my daughter's class, it turned out that

00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:45.440
we got chatting. It turned out that she had done a PhD in physics, but now she was taking her

00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:49.760
knowledge of machine learning that she learned from looking at galaxies and things like that

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:57.039
to healthcare. I told her somehow about the problem I was working on, and she said, you know,

00:09:57.039 --> 00:10:02.479
you need to do machine learning. I thought, well, I don't know. She said, you're a smart guy. You

00:10:02.479 --> 00:10:09.440
can do this. So, I thought, okay. So, I did start to do a bit of reading, and I realized that patient

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:14.080
level cancellation prediction is a machine learning problem. She was right. It was supervised

00:10:14.159 --> 00:10:20.239
learning. There was a binary classification of cancelled or completed. I realized there were

00:10:20.239 --> 00:10:23.599
some specific challenges. One of them, like I told you, there's like four or five percent

00:10:23.599 --> 00:10:31.760
cancellation rate, so there's some class imbalance. Anyway, at this point, I was fortunate to come

00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:37.679
across the applied predictive modeling book by Max Kuhn, and through that, the carrot package,

00:10:37.679 --> 00:10:41.919
I wish tidy models had been available in those days, but that really got me started,

00:10:41.919 --> 00:10:46.239
and I was able to actually do some machine learning. Another slide I don't want you to

00:10:46.239 --> 00:10:52.080
really look at in detail, but following Max's advice from his book, I was able to set up a

00:10:52.080 --> 00:10:56.880
fairly standard training pipeline, and we used fairly standard algorithms, and we got some

00:10:56.880 --> 00:11:02.960
useful data. Again, just want to show you the complexity. My next slide, I'm going to show you

00:11:02.960 --> 00:11:08.880
some of the conclusions. So, we wanted to find some actionable insights from this patient level

00:11:08.880 --> 00:11:14.159
prediction. The first thing I discovered was actually it was good enough for risk stratification.

00:11:14.159 --> 00:11:20.239
We got pretty good models, especially for the second and third causes, the no-show and MPO

00:11:20.239 --> 00:11:26.400
violation. The patient illness was rather more difficult to predict, and perhaps that's unsurprising

00:11:26.400 --> 00:11:34.080
because kids do get sick. What we found was that the strongest predictor was if patients

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:42.880
had cancelled for surgery before. Importantly, we found out that kids who came from socioeconomically

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:48.719
disadvantaged backgrounds were at the highest risk of cancellation, and so going back to when

00:11:48.719 --> 00:11:53.760
I was talking about the Institute of Medicine's dimensions of quality, it turns out that surgery

00:11:53.760 --> 00:11:59.039
cancellation is an important contributor to disparities in access to surgical care.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:04.799
In the Cincinnati area, interestingly, this is confounded by race, and this is a point that I want

00:12:04.799 --> 00:12:12.559
to come back to in a moment. What was very important to discover is that cancellation

00:12:12.559 --> 00:12:17.359
wasn't really the fault of any one particular surgical specialty as such. It was really down

00:12:17.359 --> 00:12:23.119
to the demographics of their patient populations, and this enabled me to go back to this cancellation

00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:31.359
myth, dental patients are the worst for not showing up. Well, they are in the sense of their

00:12:31.359 --> 00:12:38.479
backgrounds, but it's not something that the dental service is responsible for, and this takes me on

00:12:38.479 --> 00:12:45.280
to another potential myth. It's always patients from northern Kentucky. Now, if you don't know

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:51.359
the area of Cincinnati, I didn't when I moved there from London, this is a Google map. You can

00:12:51.359 --> 00:12:56.880
see the hospital in the middle. Although the city of Cincinnati itself is squarely within Ohio,

00:12:56.880 --> 00:13:01.440
a good proportion of the greater Cincinnati region, a bit below the river at the bottom there,

00:13:01.440 --> 00:13:07.280
is in northern Kentucky, so that's what we're talking about. Now, we come on to another

00:13:07.280 --> 00:13:15.840
important influence for me. John Snow, a fellow Brit, is an amazing man for pioneering two

00:13:15.840 --> 00:13:20.640
things that are now quite close to my heart. First of all, anesthesia safety, but secondly,

00:13:20.640 --> 00:13:26.719
epidemiology. You might have heard the story about how he mapped cholera cases in London,

00:13:27.840 --> 00:13:34.320
identified that one particular well was at the centre of where the cases were,

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:39.760
they removed the handle from the well, and the cholera cases went away. At least this is the way

00:13:39.760 --> 00:13:46.320
they told the story. So, I wanted to do some plotting too. Moved on a little bit with my

00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:52.080
R skills at this point. I started plotting cancellation rates by zip codes, and you can

00:13:52.080 --> 00:13:58.719
see the highest rates are in red here. So, yes, the northern Kentucky patients, there is an area of

00:13:58.719 --> 00:14:03.280
northern Kentucky that's a hot spot, but actually there are hot spots in other parts as well.

00:14:04.080 --> 00:14:06.559
So, another myth that we were able to bust.

00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:13.840
Moving on a little bit further, I started taking a slightly different approach. Now, I've got the

00:14:13.840 --> 00:14:21.440
same data effectively in the left-hand panel here. So, this time I've moved into actually

00:14:22.239 --> 00:14:27.599
looking at something more granular than zip codes, because I realised zip codes were actually not a

00:14:27.599 --> 00:14:33.760
good idea. You can see that there is a heavy cluster of cancellation in the middle of the

00:14:33.760 --> 00:14:40.559
panel there. We also wanted to look at some stuff that we'd used before for the medical record.

00:14:40.559 --> 00:14:46.880
So, like the race in the middle panel, and also who was paying for the surgery, which was a marker

00:14:46.880 --> 00:14:53.440
of socioeconomic disadvantage on the right-hand side. What was interesting looking at this is that

00:14:53.440 --> 00:14:59.760
there was more similarity between race and cancellations than there was with poverty as such.

00:14:59.760 --> 00:15:07.440
Now, I wanted to know more, and I couldn't get any more data out of the medical record. So,

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:13.119
actually, like our first speaker today, I used tidy census to pull a lot of data from the American

00:15:13.119 --> 00:15:17.599
Community Survey and was able to find out a lot more about the neighbourhoods in which families live.

00:15:19.599 --> 00:15:28.320
From this, we were able to set up some machine learning models of cancellation rate in a

00:15:28.320 --> 00:15:36.880
geospatial sense. The areas in red hatching here are where the middle model gives a pretty

00:15:36.880 --> 00:15:42.080
good prediction, and basically that covers most of the densely populated area of Cincinnati.

00:15:42.799 --> 00:15:46.320
From this, we're able to find out a whole lot more about the neighbourhoods where

00:15:46.960 --> 00:15:52.559
patients with high cancellation rates were living. And again, I'm going to just go through that a

00:15:52.559 --> 00:15:58.640
little bit more. So, first of all, we did find that American Community Survey data did help us

00:15:58.640 --> 00:16:03.919
compared to things that weren't available in the patient chart. We found that affected families

00:16:03.919 --> 00:16:09.039
tend to live in dense urban neighbourhoods with low literacy levels. They're often very close to

00:16:09.039 --> 00:16:13.280
the hospital campus, so offering a ride could be quite cost-effective because it would only be for

00:16:13.280 --> 00:16:18.880
a mile or two. We found that African-American families were disproportionately affected,

00:16:18.880 --> 00:16:24.239
which seemed to fit with what we found before. We realised that we could potentially improve

00:16:24.239 --> 00:16:29.679
the cultural competency of our communications with Black families. We also found that our

00:16:29.679 --> 00:16:34.640
communications with non-native speakers of English were actually not a great problem

00:16:34.640 --> 00:16:37.599
in the Cincinnati area, so our interpreting service was doing a great job.

00:16:40.719 --> 00:16:47.919
So, just to conclude, on a whim, in I think 2013, I downloaded RStudio because there was

00:16:47.919 --> 00:16:55.280
no financial barrier to entry. A lot of things have happened. I was lucky to get an R grant,

00:16:55.919 --> 00:17:02.320
a federal R grant, which academics know is very sought after. I became a co-advisor to a medical

00:17:02.320 --> 00:17:07.119
informatics PhD student. I developed and we disseminated an understanding of children's

00:17:07.119 --> 00:17:10.959
surgery cancellation, which I've given you some highlights of just now, and got a couple of

00:17:10.959 --> 00:17:16.079
publications out of it. I wanted to take this further and actually reduce cancellation rates,

00:17:16.079 --> 00:17:20.319
and I submitted a number of applications, and unfortunately they were not successful,

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:27.520
and then COVID happened. For family reasons, I had to move to the East Coast,

00:17:27.520 --> 00:17:31.520
but by this point I'd developed quite a lot of proficiency in R and in data science techniques,

00:17:31.520 --> 00:17:36.239
and I was lucky to get a faculty position at the University of Pennsylvania and the Children's

00:17:36.239 --> 00:17:42.160
Hospital of Philadelphia, and I am continuing research using data science in some different

00:17:42.160 --> 00:17:50.560
areas now. Finally, some shout outs and pointers. Along my journey, Google has been my constant

00:17:50.560 --> 00:17:58.560
guide. I've used, Fran has been extremely helpful, and early on Stack Overflow was often where I was

00:17:58.560 --> 00:18:05.359
directed. R bloggers and various other blog sites have been incredibly helpful, and I've got here

00:18:05.359 --> 00:18:09.439
two people who are now positive employees whose blogs I've followed quite a lot in the past.

00:18:10.319 --> 00:18:16.400
Increasingly over time, I found more and more online books here through Bookdown, and GitHub

00:18:16.400 --> 00:18:20.959
was also incredibly helpful to me. I hope that that's going to be helpful to somebody else in

00:18:20.959 --> 00:18:32.719
the future. Thank you. I'm not, and I live in Cincinnati currently, and I can say data or not,

00:18:32.719 --> 00:18:40.800
it is always Northern Kentucky. A few questions we have time for. What packages did you use for

00:18:40.800 --> 00:18:46.800
that hotspotting graphic that you showed? I remember that was old, so I think I used SP.

00:18:47.920 --> 00:18:53.439
Now everything I do geospatial will be ESSA. Okay. Was it difficult getting the data you

00:18:53.439 --> 00:18:58.239
needed to answer these medical questions? Were there HIPAA concerns? There were definitely HIPAA

00:18:58.239 --> 00:19:02.880
concerns. All the geocoding that I showed you, I actually had to set up. I learned a little bit of

00:19:02.880 --> 00:19:08.239
Ruby just to set up a geocoding package, so I didn't have to send stuff out to Google. Okay.

